```java
public class Stack {
    private int maxSize; // Maximum size of the stack
    private int top; // Index of the top element in the stack
    private int[] stackArray; // Array to hold the elements of the stack

    public Stack(int size) {
        maxSize = size;
        stackArray = new int[maxSize];
        top = -1; // Initially, the stack is empty, so top is set to -1
    }

    // Method to add an item to the stack
    public void push(int value) {
        if (top < maxSize - 1) { // Check if there's space in the stack
            stackArray[++top] = value; // Increment top and then add the value
        } else {
            System.out.println("Stack Overflow");
        }
    }

    // Method to remove an item from the stack
    public int pop() {
        if (top >= 0) { // Check if the stack is not empty
            return stackArray[top--]; // Return the top element and then decrement top
        } else {
            System.out.println("Stack Underflow");
            return -1; // Return -1 as an error code for underflow
        }
    }

    // Method to peek at the top item without removing it
    public int peek() {
        if (top >= 0) {
            return stackArray[top];
        } else {
            System.out.println("Stack is empty");
            return -1;
        }
    }

    // Method to check if the stack is empty
    public boolean isEmpty() {
        return (top == -1);
    }

    // Method to check if the stack is full
    public boolean isFull() {
        return (top == maxSize - 1);
    }

    // Method to get the current size of the stack
    public int size() {
        return top + 1;
    }
}
```

This `Stack` class provides basic operations such as pushing an element onto the stack (`push`), popping an element off the stack (`pop`), peeking at the top element (`peek`), checking if the stack is empty or full (`isEmpty`, `isFull`), and getting the size of the stack (`size`). This implementation uses an array to store the stack's elements and includes checks to prevent overflow and underflow conditions.

